Frequency of t is srate / bit_depth. So at 8khz srate with 8bit unsigned audio samples, 
just outputting sample count t will create a saw wave with frequency 8000/256 = 31.25hz which is approx a C1

Modulo %
Does 2 things: change pitch AND attenuate volume
E.g. `t % 128` doubles freq and halves volume
t % m, where m < 256 (or whatever the MAX_INT is) causes the output to cycle every m samples
Using formula freq = srate/bit_depth, we can determine frequency m = srate/freq and JI ratios.
E.g. we know a major 3rd has a ratio of 5:4 or 1.25:1. Then 256 / 1.25 = 204.8 ~= 205, so
`t % 205` will produce a freq that is a major 3rd higher than just `t`
This works for any expression, e.g. `(t*4) % 205` will be a major3 above `(t*4)`


( t * 9& t >>4|t * 5 & t>>7 | t*3 & t>>10) // pretty

((t>>12 & 1) * 2 - 1) // impulse or kick
(t>>5 & 0x80) // impulse or kick
idea: the falling or rising edge of a square wave produces an impulse

Mixing
(3*t % 256) / 2   + (2*t % 256) / 2
idea: need to modulo 256 and then divide by the # of sounds being mixed together so 
there isn't any aliasing from wrap-around

cool beat
(t*4 % 256) / ((t%1000) / 250)
The important part is the divisor, e.g.
```
(
(t*4 % 256)                            // base freq
/ 
2 * ((t%6000) / ((t>>4 ) % (900 + 0))) // divisor
)
```





